Pretoria - Municipal workers have gathered at Tshwane House to receive feedback from stakeholders and the local labour forum following their demand for salary increases of 18% and the stoppage of outsourcing of services. Deputy regional secretary of the South African Municipal Workers Union (Samwu), Valentine Matlala, said they are not about to embark on a strike since they had not applied to strike, but simply gathered workers to hear whether they will be paid their money. They are expected to be address by mayor Steven Mokgalapa. Traffic all around the city has been backed-up since the early hours of this morning. To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window. Taxi drivers as well as A Re Yeng buses are also being restricted from transporting passengers. One of the municipal workers said they received strict instructions from their group divisional head to report to work before 9am or face not being paid. Some of the Workers from the municipality are also standing outside Tshwane House waiting for news about their salary. Nearby shops are closed in fear of being attacked and they said that they did not want to risk being looted. Pretoria News